Competition Authority of Kenya is investigating South Africa's pay TV Naspers, after local business rivals said it has unfairly monopolised broadcasts of popular European football matches, a source at the authority has said.The business operating under MultiChoice East Africa, and which owns the DStv and Supersport brands, is the only pay-TV channel showing the English Premier League, popular among Kenyan fans.Supersport has the rights to broadcast 380 games per season live across sub-Saharan Africa, though the Premier League has also awarded free-to-air rights for some matches to Kwese Sports, owned by Econet Wireless. A source at CAK said an investigations are ongoing but declined to divulge details."We are aware of the investigation and are cooperating with the CAK. We do not believe there are any transgressions on our part," Meloy Horn, Naspers investor relations officer said.